         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1112">
               <p>A second cousin to Sir <persName>Isaac Newton</persName>, Elizabeth Ayscough
                  married Rev. <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1114.xml"/>John Hutton</persName>
                  in <date when="1705">1705</date>. <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1114.xml"
                     />Hutton</persName> (<date from="1676" to="1750">1676–1750</date>) was a
                  nonjuror who resigned his living on the ascension of <persName>William</persName>
                  and <persName>Mary</persName>. The Huttons then turned to boarding scholars at
                  Westminster School, and lived in a house adjoining that of <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2189.xml"/>Samuel Wesley Jr</persName>. in
                     <placeName>Dean&apos;s Yard, Westminster</placeName>. Elizabeth became a
                  frequent correspondent of <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2189.xml"/>Samuel
                     Jr</persName>., worrying over the directions that the Methodist revival that
                  broke out in <date when="1738">1738</date> was leading her son <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers1113.xml"/>James</persName>, <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName>, and <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
